messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path: /api/users/profile

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable for this endpoint? No. The route defines only GET and PUT for /api/users/profile (with auth protection). Other methods are not defined for this path.

- HEAD: Yes. Because Express automatically handles HEAD for routes that have a GET handler. There is a GET /api/users/profile (with protect middleware), so HEAD is effectively acceptable.

- POST: No. The only methods defined for /api/users/profile are GET and PUT.

- OPTIONS: No. There is no explicit OPTIONS handler defined for this path in the code.

- TRACE: No. Not defined in the code.

- GET: Yes. /api/users/profile has a GET handler (getUserProfile) with protect middleware.

- PUT: Yes. /api/users/profile has a PUT handler (updateUserProfile) with protect middleware.

- DELETE: No. Not defined for this path.

- PATCH: No. Not defined for this path.

Explanation:
- The endpoint for updating a user profile is defined in routes/login as router.route('/profile').get(protect, getUserProfile).put(protect, updateUserProfile); and the router is mounted under /api/users in server.js, resulting in /api/users/profile for GET and PUT (both protected by the authentication middleware).
- There are no other HTTP methods defined for /api/users/profile (no POST, DELETE, PATCH, or OPTIONS handlers). HEAD is not explicitly defined, but Express automatically provides HEAD support for GET routes, so HEAD is effectively acceptable here. OPTIONS and TRACE are not implemented in the code, so they are not acceptable for this endpoint.
